<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Oxyria digyna </i>has been the focus of ecological studies for over 50 years (see References section below). It grows in dense tufts with stems 10-20 cm high. Leaves are kidney-shaped, somewhat fleshy, and clustered at the stem base. Both flowering stems and leaf stalks are somewhat reddish. Plants produce rhizomes, but they mainly reproduce by seed. Plants are similar in appearance to rhubarb, and new growth is edible with a sour taste. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Oxyria digyna </i>is a circumpolar plant of the arctic, subarctic, and alpine areas throughout the northern hemisphere. Stands in California are local in extent and occur in locations where botanists do not usually conduct vegetation plots (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Other herbs in similar rocky subalpine to alpine locations include <i>Epilobium obcordatum, Polemonium chartaceum, P. eximium, Primula suffrutescens, </i>and <i>Saxifraga tolmiei</i>. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands occur in all mountain ranges that reach subalpine elevations in California. Taylor (1984) proposed an alliance, including the <i>Oxyria digyna-Draba lemmonii</i> association in the Sierra Nevada (M261Eo) for stands at the Harvey Monroe Hall RNA; <i>O. digyna</i> is also common in talus and scree habitats in the Sierra Nevada (M261Eh) at Lyon Peak/Needle Lake RNA and in the High Cascades (M261Df) at Antelope Creek Lakes RNA (Cheng 2004). We need more sampling and analysis to understand affinities of these stands that occur at high elevations in Californiaâ€™s mountains. </div>
</div>

	

    
